There were three eminent men of the name Caius Scribonius Curio, avus, pater, filius, Plio. h. n. vlt 41, uno sattellia Curionum in ‘qua tres corztinua serie oratores extiterunt. The first (Curio pater) was a distinguished orator (eloquen- tissimus temporibus suis de orat. 11 5 98, Brut. 5 m), who spoke inst Servius Fulvius, when accused of incest. The second is the one re erred to in the text aud again 11 5 59. He was tribune of the plebs Μ. 90, and, after serving under Sulla in Graece, became praetor Μ. 82 and consultae. 76. At the expiration of his consulship he was made pro· consul of Macedonia, where he carried the war against the barbarians as far north as the Danube, and celebrated a triumph over the Dardanians in 71 (in Pis. 5 44). An intimate friend aud supporter of Cicero, he entertained a personal eumity to Caesar, which was probably the cause why he spoke in favour of Clodius wheu accused of violating the sacra of the Bona Dea: in Μ. 57 he was made pontifex maximus. Cicero speaks highly of him as a man, (ep. ad Quint. fr. 11 3, a, iu Vatin. 5 ²4 perpetuum hostem improborum omnium, auctorem publici consilii, libertate coenmuni tuenda maxime liberum), but he did not shine asan orator, orator Latine non pessime loquebatur, sed erat indoctus, memoria nulla, artebne ridiculus, Brut. 5213,5216-217,5aao. His son was also a friend of Cicero, the first seven letters of whose second book of epistulae &santelmus are addressed to him, but unlike his father, a profligate. He was married to Fulvia, who afterwards became Antony’s wife. He was one of the main instruments in kindling the war between Caesar and Pompey and on the breaking out of the war served under Caesar and fell in battle against Juba and the Pompeian party.
